entry.title: Pass --disable-field-trial-config to tests that need it.
entry.content:
Affected tests already run without the testing config applied,

so this CL makes it explicit.



Context: Browser tests that use ScopedFeatureList and pass

params presently cause the field trial testing config to be

entirely disabled. (details: crbug.com/1491463#c8)

We plan to fix this, but some existing tests rely on this

(fail with the testing config). This CL annotates those

tests explicitly by making them specify the flag for that.



Once all the CLs updating such tests land (sharded via git

cl split), the following CL to make ScopedFeatureList not

disable the testing config can land:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4935093



As many tests are affected, it will be up to their owners

to do any necessary follow up if the tests should be made to

pass with the testing config (per the comments this CL adds).



Note: I did a best effort to have the new flag only apply to the

subset of tests that needed it when it was a single or a small

number of tests that were affected, by introducing subclasses

for the affected tests. In other cases, where lots of tests in

the same file fail, the flag is added to the original test class.



Note: The --disable-field-trial-config flag is passed simply

by name intentionally, to avoid additional complexity from

depending on components/variations and includes to reference

the existing constant for it. The name is unlikely to change and

this way, we need less complex code to add this to the tests.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: Check that Renderer tids don't belong to Browser from the Browser process
entry.content:
This change is relevant only to Chrome on Android because other

platforms don't have ADPF support.



At the moment the GPU process checks that Renderer tids don't belong to

itself and the Browser process before including them into the ADPF hint

session. This check works incorrectly (= always fails) on Beta and

Stable because the GPU process doesn't have access to the list of

threads of the Browser process. As a result, Renderer threads are

missing from the ADPF hint session. It works correctly on Canary and Dev

because the Chrome app is marked as "profileable".



With this change, the GPU process checks that Renderer tids don't belong

to itself, and then asks the Browser process to check that these tids

don't belong to Browser via a mojo message. The GPU and the Browser

processes have access to the list of the own threads (using

/proc/self/task) on all channels, so this change fixes Chrome ADPF usage

on Beta and Stable.



While this is effectively a bug fix, it's hidden behind a disabled by

default `EnableADPFAsyncThreadsVerification` feature to make sure that

we can roll it out safely and properly evaluate the impact on field

metrics for Beta and Stable.



b/302096134#comment41 has a link to the design doc with the discussion

of other options considered and the security implications.



Local testing with a custom build branded as "Chrome Beta" shows the

same behavior as the current Chrome app (i.e. Renderer threads missing

from the ADPF session) when the feature is disabled, and fixed behavior

(i.e. Renderer threads are in the ADPF session) when the feature is

enabled.

entry.title: Skip scoring URLs when deleting matches from the omnibox.
entry.content:
When a match is deleted from the omnibox, currently it kicks off URL

scoring in a posted task. Unfortunately changing the selection would

cancel the posted task, meaning listeners (including the UI) were never

updated. Making sure the posted task is not canceled fixes the bug, but

then there's a delay while the posted task completes before the UI

updates. This patch instead simply skips URL re-scoring when deleting a

match, so that listeners are immediately updated.

entry.content:
This CL reverts the change in crrev.com/c/4804050, which includes

TransportState::PAUSED in the SyncSettingsAccountState::kSignedOut.

caused by a nil GetAccountErrorUIInfo response (eg. kSignInNeedsUpdate).

This CL also introduces a simpler fix for the original crash, to skip

the error section update in case of a nil response. And thus the

which resolves the accidental crashes.

entry.title: Respect 'disable enterprise CRD' policy in FetchCrdAvailabilityInfo remote command
entry.content:
The RemoteAccessHostAllowEnterpriseRemoteSupportConnections policy is

used to prevent an enterprise admin from starting a CRD connection;

Currently it works by failing the StartCrdSession remote command,

but it's much nicer for the enterprise admin if this policy is checked

by the FetchCrdAvailabilityInfo remote command as well, since that is

supposed to tell the admin of they can start a CRD session (and if not,

tell them why).



To make this work, I also had to introduce a pref to go with this

policy.



Manual tests performed: Start CRD session when device is:

* at login screen.

* in MGS, both with and without the policy set

* in Kiosk (where the policy can not be applied).

* in affiliated user session, both with and without the policy set.

entry.title: Pass --disable-field-trial-config to tests that need it.
entry.content:
Affected tests already run without the testing config applied,

so this CL makes it explicit.



Context: Browser tests that use ScopedFeatureList and pass

params presently cause the field trial testing config to be

entirely disabled. (details: crbug.com/1491463#c8)

We plan to fix this, but some existing tests rely on this

(fail with the testing config). This CL annotates those

tests explicitly by making them specify the flag for that.



Once all the CLs updating such tests land (sharded via git

cl split), the following CL to make ScopedFeatureList not

disable the testing config can land:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4935093



As many tests are affected, it will be up to their owners

to do any necessary follow up if the tests should be made to

pass with the testing config (per the comments this CL adds).



Note: I did a best effort to have the new flag only apply to the

subset of tests that needed it when it was a single or a small

number of tests that were affected, by introducing subclasses

for the affected tests. In other cases, where lots of tests in

the same file fail, the flag is added to the original test class.



Note: The --disable-field-trial-config flag is passed simply

by name intentionally, to avoid additional complexity from

depending on components/variations and includes to reference

the existing constant for it. The name is unlikely to change and

this way, we need less complex code to add this to the tests.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: VideoTrackRecoderTest: Split to classes for TEST_F and TEST_P
entry.content:
VideoTrackRecorderTest is a google-test class for a parameterized

tests. However, TEST_F run with the class. If I call GetParam() in

VideoTrackRecorderTest, then GetParam() in TEST_F is not allowed and

caused CHECK() fatal [1].

and VideoTrackRecorderTestParam for TEST_P. So we can call GetParam()

in a member function, e.g. the constructor and thus we don't need to

call GetParam() in each TEST_P.

Server card save is the only remaining dependency between the address

and payment sync setting toggles. In order to uncouple them, this CL

conditions credit card save on address sync. This is conditioned on

the AutofillDecoupleAddressPaymentSyncSettings feature flag.



Not offering server card save for syncing users that disabled address

syncing is already the case, since payment sync can only be enabled when

address sync is. For signed-in, non-syncing users, this will be a

behavior change.



The existing code already verifies this additional condition, which was

seemingly unnecessary before this CL due to the coupling.

entry.title: Revert "frame: Flip fullscreen state on TabletModeToggled"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8af6e204ac597d1be03269520a76258af57b6aea.



Reason for revert: Causing test flakiness in

HomeLauncherBrowserNonClientFrameViewChromeOSTest.TabletModeAppCaptionButtonVisibility



Original change's description:

> frame: Flip fullscreen state on TabletModeToggled

>

> This CL fixes the behavior for both Ash and Lacros when entering tablet

> mode while immersive mode is enabled.

>

> Currently, immersive mode state is tied to fullscreen state since

> FullscreenController::ToggleBrowserFullscreenMode() eventually calls

> ImmersiveModeController::SetEnabled to align the state.

> However, OnTabletModeToggled only updates immersive mode state while

> it does not for fullscreen state. This causes the incorrect state

> where fullscreen is still enabled while tablet mode is enabled so

> that the tablet mode feature such as swiping down/up is unusable.

>

> Locked fullscreen is the only exception where immersive and fullscreen

> mode may have different states. In such case, both was_enabled and

> ShouldEnableImmersiveModeController() must be false, so it won't break

> the locked fullscreen state. This behavior is verified by

> LockedFullscreenBrowserNonClientFrameViewChromeOSTest.ToggleTabletMode

>

> This CL lets FullscreenController toggles fullscreen mode instead of

> only updating immersive mode.

entry.title: gl: make gl::GLContext store offscreen surface
entry.content:
OzoneImageBacking will start to cache glTextures soon to

avoid additional overhead of construction/destruction. However,

it needs to do that on correct contexts. Thus, the caching

mechanism has to store a correct surface that was used to initialize

the context. (https://crrev.com/c/4876722)



The easiest way to do that is to make the gl::GLContext store

the surface if it was an offscreen one when the context was

initialized. Moreover, there is a number of places that keep

the offscreen surface for the sake of initializing of a context

and making it current. Thus, this change also helps to clean

up such places and make the code look cleaner.



The following changes have been done to this CL.

1) gl::GLContext stores the gl::GLSurface iff it's the offscreen

one.

2) InitializeImpl() was added that each subclass must implement.

2) MakeCurrentDefault() was added so that the call sites can use that directly without accessing the surface if they don't care about the

surface when make current.



In the next CL, the call sites will be updated.
